text: I don't think people realize how serious this disease is. It can happen to anyone of any age and there's no cure. My dad was diagnosed when he was only 52 with dementia(the umbrella of the memory loss diseases). I thought I would have time to have my last words with him but there's no point now...he doesn't even comprehend anything. I'm 17 and my father is still alive, but what was left of him was gone 2-3 years ago. This story (Still Alice) is actually one of the lucky ones because we originally didn't even know he had dementia until we saw surveillance footage of him doing nothing for 9 hours at work.  So educate yourself on the symptoms for these diseases, because you never know when it's too late... At the very least, enjoy what you have today because it could be gone tmrw.

text: Something that a lot of people don't understand about Alzheimer's disease if they haven't witnessed it, or done real research into it, is that the people are not just loosing their long term memory. They are slowing loosing every single piece of memory they have, family, faces, childhood, how to tie their shoes, and in the very late stages their brain looses the concept of swallowing and slowly the automatic responses. That we as humans take for granted start to be lost, you no longer know how to blink, how to breathe. I myself have the. Possibility of getting this disease later in life, and I believe it is one of the most horrible and terrifying diseases out there
author: ShinigamiMischief15

text: I watched the movie and is it just me or was the way the doctor dealt with her situation brutally cold. There seemed little or no love in the way he communicated with Alice treating her as if she was a machine. I think Alzheimer's shouldn't be seen as a disease which is a problem within an otherwise ok world. Rather its like a kind of message to us a humans as a whole to think about what our lives mean to us and what is meaningful. I am not convinced that memory is all we are  or that functioning is the most important thing. The poem shared by Lydia (Kirsten Stewart) which Alice picked up was about love was the highlight. Love is the most important thing in life. Not remembering countless details which are, if one thinks about it, merely fragments of what was occurring at any given past moment anyway. I repeat. Love is what is most important. Relative to reality at large we all have Alzheimer's.
author: David Watermeyer

text: I was 18 years old when my dad was taken out of work. He was diagnosed with diabetes after the summer. It took several months until a full diagnosis was made for his condition; he had been diagnosed with advanced Alzheimer's disease. Over a year later, I'm nearly 20 years old and I have to look at my dad every single day, knowing, I'll never get my old man back. He sees me and my family as strangers, he always thinks he's at work and the worst part of it is, we have to play along. We can never correct him. The one thing I want more than anything is to have my dad back, but it will never, ever happen. He's reaching the stage where he could be placed into a nursing home any day now, I honestly don't think he will last at home with us much longer and it will break my heart when he leaves us all and is placed into a nursing home. After watching this trailer, I just sat and cried my eyes out. I hope when I am finally able to watch this film all the way through, it will open my eyes a lot more, because sometimes I don't know how to feel about my dad's condition; its not as overwhelming for me, I sat in the bath once and forced myself to cry because I just didn't feel emotional. That's all I want to feel; so then I can understand the condition more.
author: Charley J
